Condition : 18 - Prior to construction movements commencing, the developer/applicant is to register any Non-Road Mobile Machinery (NRMM) of net power between 37kW and 560kW at https://nrmm.london/ to help monitor the use of such equipment across London. Non-Road Mobile Machinery (NRMM) of net power between 37kW and 560kW used on the site of any major development in London will be required to meet the following standards: 
From 1 September 2015: 
- Stage IIIA of EU Directive 97/68/EC as a minimum, within Greater London; 
- Stage IIIB of EU Directive 97/68/EC as a minimum, within the Central Activity Zone; 
From 1 September 2020: 
- Stage IIIB of the Directive as a minimum, within Greater London; 
- Stage IV of the Directive as a minimum, within the Central Activity Zone. 
To ensure that emissions are well controlled all planning consents for major development will include relevant planning conditions to reduce these impacts. To ensure that the amenities of occupiers are protected from the poor air quality in the vicinity in accordance with Policy DM04 of the Development Management Policies DPD (adopted September 2012), the Sustainable Design and Construction SPD (adopted April 2013) and Policy 5.3 of the London Plan 2011.

Condition : 22 - The development shall be carried out in accordance with the heating and power supply information approved under details application ref. 2019/2991 dated 04/09/2019 which includes: 

- Details of the plant and its abatement system to be approved by the Council; 

- An Air Quality Assessment (AQA) for boilers to show that there will not be an unacceptable impact on local air quality. The specification of ultra-low emission boilers does not necessarily negate this requirement. The Borough will not consent development that includes energy plant that is likely to result in unacceptable pollution; 

- A screening-assessment for air quality impact shall be completed for the cumulative effect of CHP(s) (combined heat and power units) and boilers in the development. If the CHPs cannot be screened-out, then dispersion modelling of each CHP & boiler  shall be undertaken by using an appropriate modelling software and relevant data-sets; 

- All non-CHP gas-fired boilers shall meet the ultra-low standard and therefore achieve dry NOx emission levels equivalent to, or less than 40 mg/kWh; 

- CHP, gas fired boilers and other combustion plants are not allowed for developments in the Air Quality Focus Areas (AQFAs). 

- Maintenance details: all plant to be serviced and maintained according to the manufacturer's specification. In addition, a planning condition may be imposed that requires. 

- Flues from energy-plant must be at least one-metre above the highest part of the building, and in many circumstances will need to be significantly higher. The appropriate stack height should be determined using dispersion modelling not by using the Memorandum on Chimney Heights or the Technical Guidance Note (Dispersion) (known as a D1 calculation), which are not suitable when considering annual mean NO2 concentrations. Flues should not be 'hidden' behind structures likely to impact of the dispersion of emissions. 

